      <bioghist id="aspace_ca713ab336ff01050dc95dbb7f9a2c07">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Arthur Ware Locke was born in 1883 in Cambridge Massachusetts to Mr. and Mrs. Warren A. Locke. He graduated from Harvard University in 1905 and studied music in Berlin for the next two years as a travelling fellow of the Harvard Graduate School. He taught music at a number of institutions, including Brown University, Washburn College, and the University of Wisconsin, before coming to Smith as Professor of Music in 1915. At Smith, Locke taught Wagner, Beethoven, and piano, as well as performing for the community in the weekly faculty concerts. Locke was also responsible for the acquisition of definitive editions of Bach, Beethoven, Brahms and Schubert for the college, a collection that was named the Locke Collection in 1969. During his time at Smith, Locke also compiled <title render="italic">Selected Lists of Choruses for Women's Voices</title>, which went through three editions in his lifetime. Locke retired in 1952. In 1968, his wife, Margaret Griswold Locke passed away. They had had three children together. Arthur Locke died one year later.</p>  
      </bioghist>
